## What's actually going on

If you have spent any time in nature you likely have seen a deer path in the woods. These paths are well worn, trampled, and have served as a familiar passageway to the animals that have become reliant upon them.

In a similar way, our brain builds neural pathways of familiarity. When a person first uses a substance or engages in a behavior (like gambling, scrolling, or pornography), the brain releases a flood of dopamine. A new path is created. Faint at first, over time the path becomes well-worn, accessible, instinctive.

We are however, body *and* soul. There are clear environmental and physiological factors at play, but there are also deeper spiritual implications involved in all behavior including those behaviors that feel unmanageable and unwanted.

A biblical worldview acknowledges that upbringing, brain chemistry, and trauma heavily shape our behavior, but it also points to a deeper root cause for our struggles. At our core, we possess a natural inclination toward rebellion from a holy God, a reflection of our fallen nature. The reality of sin is that it is a cruel master.

## How counseling helps

Our brains need rewired. We have instinctively walked down these "deer paths" so long that we no longer are aware of the patterns. Identifying Christ alone breaks evaluate our identity.

## When to reach out

If you're tired of the loop — not just the consequences, but the loop itself — that's enough. You don't have to hit a dramatic bottom to start. Most men wish they'd come in years before they did.
